{
	// maxRoamingHeroes: static number of heroes.
	// maxRoamingHeroesPerTown: adds over the static number for each owned town
	// - the formula doesn't go over perPlayerOnMapCap in gameConfig.json. Bump that to 16 or more for higher difficulty
	// - example: 3 + 2 * towns (owned towns = 3) = 8 (would have been 9, but 8 is the default perPlayerOnMapCap, so 8)
	// maxPass: number of cycles (find, prioritize and execute) for map activities within a turn
	// maxPriorityPass: number of cycles within each pass of maxPass for town management mostly, including buying heroes
	// - this becomes strategically important later in the game, so the AI can do its "house chores" before more important actions on the map
	// - if maxPass or maxPriorityPass is reached, AI's turn is stopped even if it could have done many more things
	// - acts as an artificial limit to how much it can work within a turn
	// mainHeroTurnDistanceLimit: number of turns as limit for the MAIN (fighting) heroes
	// threatTurnDistanceLimit: used for DangerHitMapAnalyzer, you'll probably never need to touch that
	// maxGoldPressure: used for determining if the AI player has a problem with gold or not, determining what it can do with it
	// updateHitmapOnTileReveal: used for DangerHitMapAnalyzer, you'll probably never need to touch that
	// useTroopsFromGarrisons: allows AI to use troops from garrisons together with cc->getStartInfo()->restrictedGarrisonsForAI()
	// useOneWayMonoliths: allows AI to use one way Monoliths (2026.01.03 currently buggy, so false)
	// openMap: allows AI to see the entire map from the beginning, like a cheat. Requires a LOOOOOT more CPU
	// allowObjectGraph: it's an internal mechanism for openMap
	// pathfinderBucketsCount: buckets don't exist anymore, but this value is multiplied with pathfinderBucketSize to give the total alloed nodes per position
	// pathfinderBucketSize: multiplied with pathfinderBucketsCount to give the total alloed nodes per position
	// - example: 3 and 8 or 1 and 32 both translate into a single bucket with spaces for 32 nodes
	// - a higher storage capacity becomes necessary later in the game
	// - things that go into those buckets with their respective logs that you can search in the code for (step order is approximate):
	// - P:Step0 AINodeStorage::getInitialNodes Failed to allocate node at %s[%d]
	// - P:Step1 AINodeStorage::calculateNeighbours Failed to allocate node at %s[%d]
	// - P:Step2A AILayerTransitionRule::tryUseSpecialAction Failed to allocate node at %s[%d].
	// - P:Step2B AIMovementAfterDestinationRule::bypassQuest Failed to allocate node at %s[%d].
	// - P:Step2C AIMovementAfterDestinationRule::bypassBattle Failed to allocate node at %s[%d].
	// - P:Step3 AINodeStorage::calculateTeleportations Failed to allocate node at %s[%d]
	// - P:Step4 HeroChainCalculationTask::addHeroChain Failed to allocate node at %s[%d]
	// - P:Step5 TownPortalFinder createTownPortalNode Failed to allocate node at %s[%d]
	// retreatThresholdRelative: how close to death (% of army) to be before AI considers retreating
	// retreatThresholdAbsolute: how close to death (strength of army) to be before AI considers retreating
	// safeAttackRatio: extra ratio added on top of hero's strength to determine if it's stronger than the enemy (danger)
	// - general formula: heroStrength > dangerStrength * safeAttackRatio
	// maxArmyLossTarget: how much (% of army) the AI is willing to lose before it considers getting into a battle
	// - this is an approximation and doesn't guarantee winning the battle due to many army particularities and battle styles
	// - this becomes 100% if AI player loses all towns, it's willing to risk it all
	// - example: the higher the value, the higher the chance it will die in a battle
	// - example: beginners are more likely to loose their heroes, thus pawn level also has a higher percentage here
	// useFuzzy: a different engine for calculating and prioritizing what to do (2026.01.03 currently unfinished in unknown state, so false)

